\begin_layout Subsection
Triangles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We mentioned in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Implementation-in-GeoGebra"

\end_inset

 that our current technological possibilities are limited to deal with equations
 only.
 Thus Theorem 1 cannot be observed by the Relation Tool at the moment, either.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a better case with Theorems 2 and 3.
 In Theorem 2 we have to show that a sum of two expressions (or areas) of
 squares equals to another square.
 Before constructing triange 
\begin_inset Formula $ABC$
\end_inset

 we need to constraint for example point 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 to lie on the line 
\begin_inset Formula $b'$
\end_inset

 (which lies on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and perpendicular to 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

) to ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $ABC\triangle$
\end_inset

 is right.
 Now we can define squares 1, 2 and 3 by using the Regular Polygon Tool
 in GeoGebra.
 To compare their areas we need to create the sum of objects 
\emph on
square1
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
square2
\emph default
 as a number object, namely 
\emph on
sum
\emph default
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Mat1-Th2"

\end_inset

).
 Now 
\emph on
square3
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
sum
\emph default
 can be compared by the Relation Tool 
\emph on
numerically
\emph default
